c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Running a large language model today means wrestling with two hard truths: they’re expensive to operate, and their memory demands are ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2209.14352","children":"growing faster than Moore’s Law can keep up"}],". Enter Multiverse Computing, which this week announced a compressed version of an OpenAI model that—according to its claims—",["$","strong",null,{"children":"halves memory requirements"}]," without sacrificing performance. The pitch is simple: lower infrastructure costs, wider accessibility, and maybe even a way to run advanced AI on hardware that would normally choke on it.\nBut here’s the catch: compression isn’t new. Companies like ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://huggingface.co/blog","children":"Hugging Face"}]," have been shrinking models for years, and NVIDIA’s ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://developer.nvidia.com/tensorrt","children":"TensorRT-LLM"}]," already optimizes inference for deployment. What Multiverse is selling isn’t just a tool—it’s a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"philosophy"}],". Their tagline, ",["$","em",null,{"children":"“Rewriting the blueprint, not removing bricks,”"}]," suggests a structural overhaul rather than incremental tweaks. That’s a bold claim in an industry where most ‘innovations’ are ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.theregister.com/2023/11/15/ai_hype_cycle/","children":"rebranded efficiency gains"}],".\nThe practical question isn’t whether compression works (it does), but ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"who it works for"}],". For cloud providers, halving memory use could mean packing more tenants onto the same servers, improving margins without passing savings along. For enterprise users, it might mean running models locally on ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.tomshardware.com/news/nvidia-rtx-4090-ai-performance","children":"mid-range GPUs"}]," instead of renting A100 clusters. And for developers? Early signals suggest the biggest win isn’t raw cost but ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"flexibility"}],"—deploying models in environments where they previously wouldn’t fit, like edge devices or budget-conscious startups.\nYet the fine print matters. Multiverse’s approach leans on ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"quantum-inspired algorithms"}]," (a term that ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://spectrum.ieee.org/quantum-computing","children":"raises eyebrows"}]," among purists), and their benchmarks aren’t public. OpenAI’s models are notoriously opaque about compression tradeoffs—does halving memory mean doubling latency? Or accepting a 5% drop in accuracy on niche tasks? The company hasn’t said. What’s clear is that this isn’t about making AI ",["$","em",null,{"children":"cheap"}],"—it’s about making it ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"less prohibitively expensive"}]," for a sliver of players who were already in the game.\nThe timing is telling. With AI infrastructure costs ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.cnbc.com/2023/10/26/ai-costs-are-soaring-for-big-tech-companies-like-meta-google.html","children":"spiraling"}]," and regulators eyeing energy use, compression isn’t just a feature—it’s a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"necessity"}],". But necessity doesn’t guarantee adoption. The real test isn’t whether Multiverse’s tech works in a demo. It’s whether companies trust it enough to bet their production workloads on it."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,"$L14","$L15"]}],"\n","$L16"]}]
